I don't think it's wise to automate this. It should be plain and obvious to users that they are using private API here. We don't give any compatibility guarantees about private API after all. They need to recompile for every new minor version of Qt. 

Also, we (and others!) should strive to write QML modules that expose all their QML types as public C++ API. Automatically linking against private C++ API will hide manual usage of the same private API, with potentially nasty effects on compatibility.

i found that answer mildly confusing, so here goes my interpretation:

i think fundamentally the answer is yes, in the longer run we want this to be implemented via a (named) provider.

but this raises an interesting question: we wouldn't want to implement this via a scoped provider, because that's legacy, and would require listing it in qbsModuleProviders if the user does an override of unrelated providers (unless we add a magic keyword "scoped" after all).
but this does sound like something rather specific, so implementing it via a package (actually multiple?) for the manual provider requires making the latter rather extensible.

i see a minor problem with a later added package/provider overriding the now added module, because that would require overriding qbsModuleSources (QBS-1658). priorities wouldn't help here, because the provider wouldn't be even run if a native module is found. otoh, we'd likely remove the module at the same time we'd add the package, so the problem wouldn't actually arise in the first place.

ok, I see that you approach the issue from a qbs dev team side.
Let's see it from a qbs user perspective (me):
I want to use kdsoap in my qbs project. It doesn't provide any pkg-config and I also need to write some rules so I create a local module in my project.
Works fine for me...
Because I think my work could be useful to others, I want to share it.
Here we are now.
First step is to properly split into different modules in order to allow other sources to provide the same submodule: kdsoap.client, kdsoap.server and kdsoap.tools.
So conan would be able to provide kdsoap.tools instead of "local" one.
Second step (when named provider and package will be integrated): create a named provider, a package and remove the module from qbs.
I have some doubts that a "normal" user will go through those steps. As far as I understand providers, they are a pain to write. There is no access to probes for example. The "scoped" qt one fully rely on qmake, which is a kind of qt probe itself.
I also don't think that a user will bother rewriting his module for the sake of integrating it in a package.
But being able to "move" a hand craft module to a named provider could really help people sharing their work and improve qbs.

Patch Set 2:

the distinction of perspectives doesn't really make sense, as the dev perspective is obviously a superset of the user perspective. you can differentiate by tactical vs strategic perspective, though.

in any case, the difference doesn't matter for my initial comment, as providers don't change how users use modules, only how the modules come to be and what they contain. providers aim to outsource all the detection intelligence to "factories", so dumb modules (which are equivalent to qbs' own module exporter) are auto-generated. this is good for flexibility and scalability.
it's correct that writing providers is currently a bit of a pita; corresponding jira tasks exist (authored by me, mostly).

kdsoap/kdsoap.qbs // client runtime, will come from "manual" provider
kdsoap-server/kdsoap-server.qbs // server runtime, will come from "manual" provider

> What I still don't understand: the layout should try to prevent any issue when moving to the package system.
> Let's say KDSoap also comes from conan, then potentially KDSoap.client/server/compiler modules will come from conan. But conan won't provide qbs code for Rules and FileTagger.

Correct. The actual code should be in the "real" module shipped with Qbs which depend on the modules that are shipped with conan (runtime and the compiler; I still not sure about compiler though).
See https://github.com/qbs/qbs/blob/master/share/qbs/modules/capnproto/cpp/capnprotocpp.qbs#L38 - it depends on the "capnp" which is created by the fallback provider (== comes from pkg-config)

> Will the package provide that?
No, package merely give the provider additional properties which help provider to setup the module correctly (e.g. in the example above the generated "capnp" module actually maps to the "capnproto" package in Conan - we need the (conanPackageName) property in the "capnp" package that tells the provider that it is actually called "capnproto")

> In the actual layout the rules can't be in the client/server modules because of that.

No, the idea was that they should be there^^

> And they can't be in KDSoap/kdsoap.qbs because the rule is different between client and server (unless I tell the compiler to generate both codes, which could actually simplify things).

Correct

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

The enabled version of the icons is not bright enough in my opinion. It should match the color of other icons. Currently it still looks disabled compared to other icons.

With Align view to Camera functionality it is possible to make the edit camera rotate/scale in ways that is not normally possible, which breaks the normal edit camera functionality and even gizmos and selection when aligned camera has scaling. 

What's worse, resetting the puppet doesn't fix the issue with rotation, as edit camera is restored to whatever rotation it was before. The only ways to restore edit camera rotation are to either align to a more sensible camera, or click on axis helper on top right corner to align camera to some axis.

This issue needs to be addressed somehow. Either by disallowing weird scaling/rotation when aligning, or having a clear way to reset the edit camera orientation. Up to UX to decide how this should be handled.

subject: QItemSelectionModel: use new flagsChanged() signal

values.-1: I would prefer this is not merged as is
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message:
Patch Set 3:

Hi, here we have a similar case as in
https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/346592/

When an item is marked as "not selectable", this might change the selection, which currently fails to emit the selectionChanged signal.

This is the best solution I can come up with at the moment. But I am not satisfied. Using this architecture, I am not able to pass which cells have been selected/unselected when emitting the selectionChanged signal.
To know which cells got selected/unselected, one could introduce a new signal like "flagsAboutToBeChanged" in QAbstractItemModel, and then hook into this instead of the dataChanged signal which I use now.

Do you see a better way of solving this problem?
Uploaded patch set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased.

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 3:
> This is the best solution I can come up with at the moment. But I am not satisfied. Using this architecture, I am not able to pass which cells have been selected/unselected when emitting the selectionChanged signal.
> To know which cells got selected/unselected, one could introduce a new signal like "flagsAboutToBeChanged" in QAbstractItemModel, and then hook into this instead of the dataChanged signal which I use now.

I agree that flagsAboutToBeChanged() is the best solution. It's probably time to introduce that.

Patch Set 8:

(2 comments)

This lacks documentation for FlagsRole (and a mention of it in the commit log).

It's going to be a bit tricky, because it's not like handling FlagsRole in data() replaces reimplementing the flags() virtual method, for instance. So (apart from internally in QStandardItemModel, but nobody cares about that) FlagsRole is really ONLY meaningful for the dataChanged() signal. This needs to be clearly documented....

Patch Set 8:

David, maybe we should abandon this and go for a new flagsChanged() signal?

I however struggle a bit to come up with a good interface.

For example, for inserting a row, there are:
1. The signal rowsAboutToBeInserted(const QModelIndex&, int, int, QPrivateSignal)
2. The signal rowsInserted(const QModelIndex&, int, int, QPrivateSignal)
3. The protected method beginInsertRows(const QModelIndex&, int, int)
4. The protected method endInsertRows()

So for introducing a flagsChanged signal, would we also need those four?
Like e.g.
1. The signal flagsAboutToBeChanged(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags, QPrivateSignal)
2. The signal flagsChanged(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags, QPrivateSignal)
3. The protected method beginChangeFlags(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags)
4. The protected method endChangeFlags()

Patch Set 8:

A proper signal for flags would certainly be cleaner. It's just that you'll have to adapt all proxies to forward it along, whereas they already do that for dataChanged().

> So for introducing a flagsChanged signal, would we also need those four?
> Like e.g.
> 1. The signal flagsAboutToBeChanged(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags, QPrivateSignal)
> 2. The signal flagsChanged(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags, QPrivateSignal)
> 3. The protected method beginChangeFlags(const QModelIndex& topLeft, const QModelIndex &bottomRight, Qt::ItemFlags newFlags)
> 4. The protected method endChangeFlags()

The beginFoo and endFoo methods are only useful because of the handling of persistent model indexes in the base class. You don't need them for a simple flagsChanged() signal, which is much more similar to dataChanged(). It has been said that dataAboutToBeChanged() would be useful too, so indeed we could from the start have the AboutToBe signal for flags. Which would mean 1 and 2 from your list. But only those.

Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

Maybe I'm missing something but this should be deterministic by crossing the current state of the selection.
The only possible reaction to a flag change is a loss of selection so you could just iterate on indexes passed by dataChanged and check that they can still be selected.
There is no way of having a reliable and generic way to select items that became selectable after a flag change.
I'm also not convinced fagsAboutToBeChanged is necessary.
IMHO flags is either considered static (as it is now) or is considered as a property of the data (like font/background/etc.). I'm not ecstatic, however, running a hybrid of the 2 as we are trying to do here

Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> (1 comment)
> 
> Maybe I'm missing something but this should be deterministic by crossing the current state of the selection.
> The only possible reaction to a flag change is a loss of selection so you could just iterate on indexes passed by dataChanged and check that they can still be selected.
> There is no way of having a reliable and generic way to select items that became selectable after a flag change.
> I'm also not convinced fagsAboutToBeChanged is necessary.
> IMHO flags is either considered static (as it is now) or is considered as a property of the data (like font/background/etc.). I'm not ecstatic, however, running a hybrid of the 2 as we are trying to do here

Thanks a lot for your input Luca,

A change of flags can lead to a gain of selection or a loss of selection.
Loss of selection if an item becomes disabled or unselectable.
Gain of selection if an item becomes enabled and selectable (and it is within one selection range of QItemSelectionModel).

Or am I mistaken?

Patch Set 8:

> and it is within one selection range of QItemSelectionModel

Ah, the ranges, of course. Shouldn't it be manageable in any case? isn't it just another loop?

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> > and it is within one selection range of QItemSelectionModel
> 
> Ah, the ranges, of course. Shouldn't it be manageable in any case? isn't it just another loop?

I'll create a new patch based on your suggestions, then we can discuss there, OK?

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> > Patch Set 8:
> > 
> > > and it is within one selection range of QItemSelectionModel
> > 
> > Ah, the ranges, of course. Shouldn't it be manageable in any case? isn't it just another loop?
> 
> I'll create a new patch based on your suggestions, then we can discuss there, OK?

Thinking more about it, I don't see a way. In the dataChanged handler, we can only obtain the new flags. We don't know about the old state of the flags. So we do not know whether the selection status changed. And thus we cannot emit a correct selectionChanged signal.

Would you agree?

Patch Set 8:

> Would you agree?

Yes, indeed.

Another alternative i see is to have the previous flag saved in another role of QSIM so you could compare but whatever way you look at it this is introducing a tight coupling between QISM with an internal implementation of QSIM which is not great.
Generically speaking flags is designed as a static property so any workaround will be hack-ish.

If we want to fix it properly we'd need to redesign how flags work. Way above my pay grade so up to David to decide how to go forward

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> If we want to fix it properly we'd need to redesign how flags work. Way above my pay grade so up to David to decide how to go forward

This really really reminds me of the QSortFilterProxyModel issue that it has no access to the old data in dataChanged so it can't know what changed if it didn't already build a mapping for that subtree. And the outcome was a suboptimal solution and a TODO in everyone's head "we should add dataAboutToBeChanged".

So unless I'm missing something, it seems to me that the same reasoning applies here.
* Introduce flagsAboutToBeChanged and flagsChanged signals
* In QSIM, handle flagsAboutToBeChanged by storing (very temporarily) a copy of the old flags (for each changed index), and handle flagsChanged by comparing the flags between old and new (for each index), which allows to deselect/select as appropriate.

The contract would be that the same list of indexes must be passed in flagsAboutToBeChanged and in flagsChanged, obviously.

Apart from the fact that many models would need additional emits, any reason for this plan not to work?

And of course QSIM wouldn't really work any worse than currently for models that would still be lacking those emits, right?

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> > Patch Set 8:
> > If we want to fix it properly we'd need to redesign how flags work. Way above my pay grade so up to David to decide how to go forward
> 
> This really really reminds me of the QSortFilterProxyModel issue that it has no access to the old data in dataChanged so it can't know what changed if it didn't already build a mapping for that subtree. And the outcome was a suboptimal solution and a TODO in everyone's head "we should add dataAboutToBeChanged".
> 
> So unless I'm missing something, it seems to me that the same reasoning applies here.
> * Introduce flagsAboutToBeChanged and flagsChanged signals
> * In QSIM, handle flagsAboutToBeChanged by storing (very temporarily) a copy of the old flags (for each changed index), and handle flagsChanged by comparing the flags between old and new (for each index), which allows to deselect/select as appropriate.
> 
> The contract would be that the same list of indexes must be passed in flagsAboutToBeChanged and in flagsChanged, obviously.
> 
> Apart from the fact that many models would need additional emits, any reason for this plan not to work?
> 
> And of course QSIM wouldn't really work any worse than currently for models that would still be lacking those emits, right?

Sorry for chiming in, in the middle of the discussion. Just wondering: right now, what's the API for changing flags? Is it a model reset, or is dataChanged abused for this purpose?

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> Sorry for chiming in, in the middle of the discussion. Just wondering: right now, what's the API for changing flags? Is it a model reset, or is dataChanged abused for this purpose?

I don't think there's a proper documented API right now.

But let's see:

Some flags are simply queried "at the right time".
Double click on cell -> the view will query for ItemIsEditable. No caching, so no problem if the value changes between one action and the next. Same for drag and drop related flags.

ItemIsUserCheckable, ItemIsEnabled, ItemIsUserTristate, ItemIsAutoTristate: those flags have an effect on the painting, so I suspect most people just emit dataChanged to force a repaint. Good enough for a view/delegate repaint. But quite possibly not precise enough (because no there's no role value associated) for things that would care more about those details (like a hypothetical proxymodel which would do things differently depending on flags .... or like QItemSelectionModel, for ItemIsEnabled, and for ItemIsSelectable).

ItemNeverHasChildren by nature is supposed to be static.

I think this is why the use case never came up before. In 99% of the cases, dataChanged (or nothing) is good enough. From what I can see, only QItemSelectionModel and a hypothetical flags-based proxymodel really need flagsAboutToBeChanged/flagsChanged. Hmm. Does that make the solution overkill then? OTOH I don't see another solution, and it would certainly be consistent.

Patch Set 8:

> a TODO in everyone's head "we should add dataAboutToBeChanged".

> only QItemSelectionModel and a hypothetical flags-based proxymodel really need flagsAboutToBeChanged/flagsChanged.

If it was up to me, I'd make flags part of the data just like fonts/foreground/background/etc. QSIM already does that, wouldn't be a massive thing to do it everywhere (and introduce Qt::FlagsRole as in this patch) without any change in the API. Then it would be again a problem of "we should add dataAboutToBeChanged"

- Of course QtQuick had to go its own way and force you through that route anyways because it doesn't support flags() to begin with <shrug>
